<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="NAME"
>NAME <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<p>IPChains::PortFW - Perl module to manipulate portfw masquerading table.</p>

<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="SYNOPSIS"
>SYNOPSIS <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<pre class="sh_perl">  my $masq = new IPChains::PortFW( option =&#62; value, ... );
  $masq-&#62;append();</pre>

<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="DESCRIPTION"
>DESCRIPTION <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<p>IPChains::PortFW is an perl interface to the linux kernel port forwarding facility. You must have ipmasqadm and the portfw module installed for this module to work. A kernel compiled with CONFIG_IP_MASQUERADE_IPPORTFW would also helps.</p>

<p>It has a similar interface than the IPChains(3) module. You create an IPChains::PortFW object with new(), you can query or set attributes with the attribute() method and you add or deletes the port forwarding rules using append() or delete().</p>

<h2><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="ATTRIBUTES"
>ATTRIBUTES</a></h2>

<p>Here are the attributes valids for IPChains::PortFW.</p>

<dl>
<dt><a name="LocalAddr"
>LocalAddr</a></dt>

<dd>
<p>This is the local address from which packets will be redirected.</p>

<dt><a name="LocalPort"
>LocalPort</a></dt>

<dd>
<p>This is the port from which packets will be redirected.</p>

<dt><a name="RemAddr"
>RemAddr</a></dt>

<dd>
<p>This is the address to which the packets will be forwarded to.</p>

<dt><a name="RemPort"
>RemPort</a></dt>

<dd>
<p>This is the port to which the packets will be forwarded to.</p>

<dt><a name="Pref"
>Pref</a></dt>

<dd>
<p>This is a preferences value used for load balancing in the case when there are many possible remote destinations.</p>
</dd>
</dl>

<h2><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="METHODS"
>METHODS</a></h2>

<dl>
<dt><a name='new'></a><a name="new(_[options],_..._)"
>new( [options], ... )</a></dt>

<dd>
<p>Create a new IPChains::PortFW object and sets its attributes.</p>

<dt><a name='attribute'></a><a name="attribute(_attribute_[,_value]_)"
>attribute( attribute [, value] )</a></dt>

<dd>
<p>Get or sets an attribute. Use undef to delete a value.</p>

<dt><a name='clopts'></a><a name="clopts()"
>clopts()</a></dt>

<dd>
<p>Unset all attributes.</p>

<dt><a name='append'></a><a name="append()"
>append()</a></dt>

<dd>
<p>Append a rule to the port forwarding masquerade table as specified by the attributes of the current objects.</p>

<dt><a name='delete'></a><a name="delete()"
>delete()</a></dt>

<dd>
<p>Deletes entries in the port forwarding masquerade table. The entries matching the attributes will be deleted.</p>

<dt><a name='flush'></a><a name="flush()"
>flush()</a></dt>

<dd>
<p>Removes all entries from the port forwarding masquerade table.</p>

<dt><a name='list'></a><a name="list()"
>list()</a></dt>

<dd>
<p>Returns an array of IPChains::PortFW objects. One for each entries in the port forwarding table.</p>
</dd>
</dl>

<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="EXAMPLE"
>EXAMPLE <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<p>Redirecting http protocol to internal web server.</p>

<p>my $portfw = new IPChains::PortFW( Proto =&#62; &#39;udp&#39;, LocalAddr =&#62; &#39;199.168.1.10&#39;, LocalPort =&#62; 80, RemAddr =&#62; &#39;10.0.0.1&#39;, RemPort =&#62; 80 );</p>

<p>$portfw-&#62;append;</p>

